---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="Kalman Filter">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics">Mathematics</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>Kalman Filter</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Mathematics · Article 2 of 5</span>
        <h1>Kalman Filter</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          Least squares finds the best estimate from a batch of observations. The Kalman filter
          does something more powerful — it tracks a changing system in real time, fusing
          new measurements with a prediction of where the system should be. Every GNSS receiver
          uses a Kalman filter at its core, and understanding it explains why your position
          smooths out over time and why it takes seconds to converge after a signal gap.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>14 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#intuition">Intuition — predict then update</a></li>
          <li><a href="#state-model">State and measurement models</a></li>
          <li><a href="#equations">The five Kalman equations</a></li>
          <li><a href="#noise">Process and measurement noise</a></li>
          <li><a href="#worked-example">Worked example — 1D position tracking</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gnss-state">GNSS Kalman filter state vector</a></li>
          <li><a href="#extended">Extended Kalman filter (EKF)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#gnss-imu">GNSS/IMU integration</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="intuition">Intuition — predict then update</h2>
      <p>
        Imagine tracking a car driving down a motorway. You know it was at position x₀ moving
        at velocity v₀ one second ago. Even without a new GPS fix, you can predict where it
        probably is now: x_predicted = x₀ + v₀ · Δt. When a new GPS measurement arrives, you
        combine your prediction with the measurement — weighting each by how much you trust it.
        If your motion model is accurate, you trust the prediction. If GPS has good signal,
        you trust the measurement. The Kalman filter formalises exactly this trade-off.
      </p>

      <div class="intuition-visual">
        <div class="iv-step">
          <div class="iv-num">1</div>
          <div class="iv-title">Predict</div>
          <div class="iv-desc">Use motion model to project state forward in time. Uncertainty grows because the model is imperfect.</div>
          <div class="iv-formula">x̂⁻ = F·x̂ₖ₋₁</div>
        </div>
        <div class="iv-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="iv-step">
          <div class="iv-num">2</div>
          <div class="iv-title">Measure</div>
          <div class="iv-desc">New observation arrives. It is noisy but carries real information about the current state.</div>
          <div class="iv-formula">z = Hx + r</div>
        </div>
        <div class="iv-arrow">→</div>
        <div class="iv-step iv-update">
          <div class="iv-num">3</div>
          <div class="iv-title">Update</div>
          <div class="iv-desc">Fuse prediction and measurement. Weight each by its uncertainty. Uncertainty shrinks — better than either alone.</div>
          <div class="iv-formula">x̂ = x̂⁻ + K·(z − Hx̂⁻)</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The key insight is that the Kalman filter is <strong>optimal</strong> — under the
        assumption of Gaussian noise and a linear model, it produces the minimum variance
        unbiased estimate. No other linear estimator can do better.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="state-model">State and measurement models</h2>
      <p>
        The Kalman filter operates on two models:
      </p>

      <div class="model-cards">
        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-title">State transition model</div>
          <div class="model-eq">xₖ = Fₖ xₖ₋₁ + wₖ</div>
          <div class="model-desc">
            Describes how the state evolves from one epoch to the next.
            <strong>xₖ</strong> = state vector at time k (position, velocity, clock, ambiguities).
            <strong>F</strong> = state transition matrix (encodes the motion model).
            <strong>w</strong> = process noise — unmodelled accelerations, clock drift fluctuations
            (w ~ N(0, Q), zero-mean Gaussian with covariance Q).
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="model-card">
          <div class="model-title">Measurement model</div>
          <div class="model-eq">zₖ = Hₖ xₖ + rₖ</div>
          <div class="model-desc">
            Relates the state to what is actually observed.
            <strong>z</strong> = measurement vector (pseudoranges, carrier phases).
            <strong>H</strong> = design matrix (partial derivatives — same as in least squares).
            <strong>r</strong> = measurement noise (r ~ N(0, R), zero-mean Gaussian with covariance R).
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="equations">The five Kalman equations</h2>
      <p>
        The Kalman filter alternates between two phases every epoch: <strong>prediction</strong>
        and <strong>update</strong>. Each phase has equations for the state estimate and its
        covariance matrix P (which encodes how uncertain we are about each state element).
      </p>

      <div class="kalman-equations">
        <div class="ke-phase">
          <div class="ke-phase-title">Prediction phase</div>
          <div class="ke-eq">
            <div class="ke-num">1</div>
            <div class="ke-content">
              <div class="ke-name">State prediction</div>
              <div class="ke-formula">x̂ₖ⁻ = Fₖ x̂ₖ₋₁</div>
              <div class="ke-desc">Project the previous state estimate forward using the motion model.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="ke-eq">
            <div class="ke-num">2</div>
            <div class="ke-content">
              <div class="ke-name">Covariance prediction</div>
              <div class="ke-formula">Pₖ⁻ = Fₖ Pₖ₋₁ Fₖᵀ + Qₖ</div>
              <div class="ke-desc">Propagate uncertainty forward. Adding Q reflects that uncertainty grows between epochs due to unmodelled dynamics.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="ke-phase ke-update-phase">
          <div class="ke-phase-title">Update phase</div>
          <div class="ke-eq ke-key">
            <div class="ke-num">3</div>
            <div class="ke-content">
              <div class="ke-name">Kalman gain</div>
              <div class="ke-formula">Kₖ = Pₖ⁻ Hₖᵀ (Hₖ Pₖ⁻ Hₖᵀ + Rₖ)⁻¹</div>
              <div class="ke-desc">The gain K balances prediction uncertainty Pₖ⁻ against measurement noise Rₖ. High K = trust measurement. Low K = trust prediction.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="ke-eq">
            <div class="ke-num">4</div>
            <div class="ke-content">
              <div class="ke-name">State update</div>
              <div class="ke-formula">x̂ₖ = x̂ₖ⁻ + Kₖ (zₖ − Hₖ x̂ₖ⁻)</div>
              <div class="ke-desc">Correct the prediction using the innovation (zₖ − Hₖx̂ₖ⁻) — the difference between what was measured and what was predicted.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="ke-eq">
            <div class="ke-num">5</div>
            <div class="ke-content">
              <div class="ke-name">Covariance update</div>
              <div class="ke-formula">Pₖ = (I − Kₖ Hₖ) Pₖ⁻</div>
              <div class="ke-desc">Uncertainty shrinks after each measurement update. The update always reduces P — the filter becomes more confident.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Innovation — the key diagnostic:</strong> The term (zₖ − Hₖx̂ₖ⁻) is called
          the <strong>innovation</strong> or measurement residual. If the filter is working
          correctly, innovations should be zero-mean, white (uncorrelated in time) and Gaussian.
          Large or correlated innovations indicate model mismatch, outliers or unmodelled errors.
          Monitoring innovations is the primary filter health diagnostic in production receivers.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="noise">Process and measurement noise</h2>
      <p>
        Choosing the noise covariance matrices Q and R is the most important — and most difficult
        — part of designing a Kalman filter. They control the filter's behaviour:
      </p>

      <div class="noise-table">
        <div class="nt-row nt-header">
          <span>Matrix</span>
          <span>Meaning</span>
          <span>Too small</span>
          <span>Too large</span>
        </div>
        <div class="nt-row">
          <span class="nt-sym">Q</span>
          <span>Process noise — how much does the true state wander from the model?</span>
          <span class="warn">Filter too slow to track real dynamics. Position lags during acceleration.</span>
          <span class="warn">Filter ignores useful information from previous state. Noisy output.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="nt-row">
          <span class="nt-sym">R</span>
          <span>Measurement noise — how noisy are the observations?</span>
          <span class="warn">Filter trusts measurements too much. Outliers corrupt the state.</span>
          <span class="warn">Filter ignores measurements. Slow to respond. Relies too much on model.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        In GNSS receivers, R is typically set from known pseudorange noise models
        (e.g. σ² = a² + b²/sin²(elevation)). Q depends on the platform dynamics —
        a pedestrian GNSS device uses a small Q for horizontal velocity; an aircraft
        needs a much larger Q.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="worked-example">Worked example — 1D position tracking</h2>
      <p>
        Track a vehicle moving at constant velocity. State: x = [position, velocity]ᵀ.
        Measurement: noisy position from GPS (σ_GPS = 3 m).
      </p>

      <div class="example-setup">
        <div class="ex-block">
          <div class="ex-title">State transition (Δt = 1 s)</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">F = ⎡1  Δt⎤ = ⎡1  1⎤</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">    ⎣0   1⎦   ⎣0  1⎦</div>
          <div class="ex-note">Position integrates velocity. Velocity unchanged (constant velocity model).</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ex-block">
          <div class="ex-title">Measurement (position only)</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">H = [1  0]</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">R = [9]  (σ² = 3² = 9 m²)</div>
          <div class="ex-note">We observe position, not velocity.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ex-block">
          <div class="ex-title">Process noise</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">Q = σ_a² ⎡Δt⁴/4  Δt³/2⎤</div>
          <div class="ex-eq">         ⎣Δt³/2   Δt² ⎦</div>
          <div class="ex-note">Continuous white noise acceleration model. σ_a = 0.1 m/s² for a car.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="example-trace">
        <div class="et-title">Filter evolution over 5 epochs (true position = 0 + 10t m)</div>
        <div class="et-table">
          <div class="et-row et-header">
            <span>k</span>
            <span>GPS (z, m)</span>
            <span>Predicted x̂⁻</span>
            <span>K (gain)</span>
            <span>Updated x̂</span>
            <span>P[0,0] (m²)</span>
          </div>
          <div class="et-row">
            <span>0</span>
            <span>—</span>
            <span>init: [0, 10]</span>
            <span>—</span>
            <span>[0, 10]</span>
            <span>100.0</span>
          </div>
          <div class="et-row">
            <span>1</span>
            <span>12.3</span>
            <span>[10.0, 10]</span>
            <span>0.918</span>
            <span>[12.1, 10]</span>
            <span>8.26</span>
          </div>
          <div class="et-row">
            <span>2</span>
            <span>19.7</span>
            <span>[22.1, 10]</span>
            <span>0.481</span>
            <span>[20.9, 10]</span>
            <span>4.71</span>
          </div>
          <div class="et-row">
            <span>3</span>
            <span>31.5</span>
            <span>[30.9, 10]</span>
            <span>0.344</span>
            <span>[31.1, 10]</span>
            <span>3.49</span>
          </div>
          <div class="et-row">
            <span>4</span>
            <span>38.2</span>
            <span>[41.1, 10]</span>
            <span>0.279</span>
            <span>[39.6, 10]</span>
            <span>2.94</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="et-note">K decreases as P converges — the filter becomes more confident and relies less on each new measurement.</div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="gnss-state">GNSS Kalman filter state vector</h2>
      <p>
        A real GNSS positioning Kalman filter carries many more state variables than the simple
        example above. The state vector in a typical RTK or PPP engine includes:
      </p>

      <div class="state-vector">
        <div class="sv-group sv-position">
          <div class="sv-group-title">Position and velocity</div>
          <div class="sv-items">
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">x, y, z</span><span class="sv-desc">ECEF position (m) — or Δx, Δy, Δz increments</span></div>
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">ẋ, ẏ, ż</span><span class="sv-desc">Velocity (m/s) — for kinematic receivers</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sv-group sv-clock">
          <div class="sv-group-title">Receiver clock</div>
          <div class="sv-items">
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">c·δt_r</span><span class="sv-desc">Receiver clock offset (m) — modelled as random walk or white noise</span></div>
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">c·δṫ_r</span><span class="sv-desc">Clock drift (m/s) — for high-quality oscillators</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sv-group sv-tropo">
          <div class="sv-group-title">Troposphere</div>
          <div class="sv-items">
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">ZWD</span><span class="sv-desc">Zenith wet delay (m) — modelled as random walk, ~0.1–1 mm/√s</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="sv-group sv-ambiguity">
          <div class="sv-group-title">Carrier phase ambiguities (PPP/RTK)</div>
          <div class="sv-items">
            <div class="sv-item"><span class="sv-sym">N_IF^i</span><span class="sv-desc">Float ambiguity for satellite i — one per satellite, constant when no cycle slip</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        The state transition for position and velocity uses a constant velocity model
        (F integrates velocity into position). The receiver clock is typically modelled
        as a random walk — its value at the next epoch is unpredictable (Q_clock is large).
        Ambiguities are modelled as constants — their transition is F = I and Q = 0,
        meaning they do not change unless a cycle slip occurs.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="extended">Extended Kalman filter (EKF)</h2>
      <p>
        The standard Kalman filter requires linear models (F and H are constant matrices).
        GNSS is fundamentally nonlinear — pseudoranges depend on position through a square root.
        The <strong>Extended Kalman Filter (EKF)</strong> handles this by linearising the
        nonlinear functions at the current state estimate each epoch.
      </p>

      <div class="formula-block">
        <div class="formula">State transition: xₖ = f(xₖ₋₁) + wₖ  (nonlinear)</div>
        <div class="formula">Measurement:     zₖ = h(xₖ) + rₖ     (nonlinear)</div>
        <div class="formula">EKF linearises:  Fₖ = ∂f/∂x|&#8203;_&#123;x̂ₖ₋₁&#125;  (Jacobian of f)</div>
        <div class="formula">                 Hₖ = ∂h/∂x|&#8203;_&#123;x̂ₖ⁻&#125;   (Jacobian of h)</div>
        <div class="formula-desc">
          The Jacobian Hₖ of the pseudorange with respect to position is exactly the direction
          cosine matrix from the least squares article — confirming that EKF prediction and
          update use the same design matrix A. The EKF is therefore the sequential
          (epoch-by-epoch) equivalent of iterative least squares.
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div>
          <strong>EKF limitations:</strong> The EKF linearises around the current estimate.
          If the estimate is far from the truth (e.g. cold start, large dynamics), the
          linearisation is inaccurate and the filter can diverge. For highly nonlinear
          systems, the Unscented Kalman Filter (UKF) or Particle Filter may perform better.
          For GNSS positioning with a reasonable initial estimate, EKF is generally sufficient.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="gnss-imu">GNSS/IMU integration</h2>
      <p>
        An Inertial Measurement Unit (IMU) measures specific force (accelerometers) and angular
        rate (gyroscopes). Integrating these gives position and attitude — but IMU errors
        accumulate rapidly. GNSS provides periodic position fixes that prevent IMU drift.
        The Kalman filter is the natural framework for combining them.
      </p>

      <div class="integration-modes">
        <div class="im-card">
          <div class="im-title">Loosely coupled</div>
          <div class="im-level">Easiest to implement</div>
          <div class="im-desc">
            The GNSS receiver outputs a position solution. The Kalman filter fuses GNSS position
            with IMU-propagated position. Works as long as GNSS can compute a valid position fix
            (≥4 satellites). Fails when GNSS is unavailable.
          </div>
          <div class="im-state">State: position, velocity, attitude, IMU biases</div>
        </div>
        <div class="im-card">
          <div class="im-title">Tightly coupled</div>
          <div class="im-level">Most common in professional systems</div>
          <div class="im-desc">
            The Kalman filter uses raw GNSS pseudoranges (not a position fix) as measurements.
            Works with fewer than 4 satellites — even 1–2 satellites provide useful constraints.
            More robust in urban canyons and under bridges.
          </div>
          <div class="im-state">State: position, velocity, attitude, IMU biases, GNSS clock</div>
        </div>
        <div class="im-card">
          <div class="im-title">Deeply coupled</div>
          <div class="im-level">High-performance / military systems</div>
          <div class="im-desc">
            IMU data feeds directly into the receiver tracking loops. Aids signal acquisition
            under high dynamics or jamming. Complex to implement. Rarely done outside
            aerospace and defence applications.
          </div>
          <div class="im-state">State: all of tightly coupled + tracking loop states</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        In tightly coupled GNSS/IMU, the IMU predicts the state between GNSS epochs (at up to
        1000 Hz), and GNSS pseudoranges update the filter at 1–10 Hz. During a GNSS outage
        (tunnel, building), the IMU continues to propagate the state — with growing uncertainty
        (P increases) until GNSS is reacquired.
      </p>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🔄</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Predict then update</div>
          <div class="summary-body">Two phases every epoch. Prediction propagates state and grows uncertainty. Update fuses new measurements and shrinks uncertainty. The Kalman gain K controls the balance.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📉</div>
          <div class="summary-title">P converges over time</div>
          <div class="summary-body">The covariance matrix P shrinks as measurements accumulate. This is why PPP accuracy improves with time — the filter has more observations to work with.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📊</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Monitor the innovation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">zₖ − Hₖx̂ₖ⁻ should be small, zero-mean and white. Large innovations indicate outliers, cycle slips or unmodelled errors. This is the primary filter health check.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🤝</div>
          <div class="summary-title">GNSS + IMU = robust navigation</div>
          <div class="summary-body">GNSS prevents IMU drift. IMU bridges GNSS outages and improves dynamics handling. Tightly coupled integration uses raw pseudoranges, working even with &lt;4 satellites.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/least-squares" class="nav-prev">← Least Squares</a>
        <a href="/learn/mathematics/ambiguity-resolution" class="nav-next">Ambiguity Resolution →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Kalman, R. E. (1960). A new approach to linear filtering and prediction problems. <em>Journal of Basic Engineering</em>, 82(1), 35–45.</li>
          <li>Grewal, M. S. & Andrews, A. P. (2015). <em>Kalman Filtering: Theory and Practice Using MATLAB</em>, 4th ed. Wiley-IEEE Press.</li>
          <li>Groves, P. D. (2013). <em>Principles of GNSS, Inertial, and Multisensor Integrated Navigation Systems</em>, 2nd ed. Artech House.</li>
          <li>Teunissen, P. J. G. & Montenbruck, O. (eds.) (2017). <em>Springer Handbook of Global Navigation Satellite Systems</em>. Chapter 12.</li>
          <li>Welch, G. & Bishop, G. (2006). An Introduction to the Kalman Filter. UNC-Chapel Hill TR 95-041. <a href="https://www.cs.unc.edu/~welch/media/pdf/kalman_intro.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">UNC →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

